1
00:00:12,320 --> 00:00:14,435
Hey, everyone. If I had to choose just

2
00:00:14,435 --> 00:00:16,115
one topic that makes all of the others

3
00:00:16,115 --> 00:00:18,195
in linear algebra start to click and which

4
00:00:18,195 --> 00:00:20,115
too often goes unlearned the first time a

5
00:00:20,115 --> 00:00:22,115
student takes linear algebra, it would be this

6
00:00:22,115 --> 00:00:25,075
one. The idea of a linear transformation and

7
00:00:25,075 --> 00:00:26,275
its relation to matrices.

8
00:00:27,020 --> 00:00:28,940
For this video, I'm just gonna focus on

9
00:00:28,940 --> 00:00:31,100
what these transformations look like in the case

10
00:00:31,100 --> 00:00:33,260
of two dimensions and how they relate to

11
00:00:33,260 --> 00:00:35,500
the idea of matrix vector multiplication.

12
00:00:35,820 --> 00:00:37,900
In particular, I wanna show you a way

13
00:00:37,900 --> 00:00:40,140
to think about matrix vector multiplication

14
00:00:40,140 --> 00:00:42,060
that doesn't rely on memorization.

15
00:00:43,085 --> 00:00:45,805
To start, let's just parse this term, linear

16
00:00:45,805 --> 00:00:46,845
transformation.

17
00:00:47,325 --> 00:00:50,205
Transformation is essentially a fancy word for function.

18
00:00:50,365 --> 00:00:52,605
It's something that takes in inputs and spits

19
00:00:52,605 --> 00:00:55,245
out an output for each one. Specifically, in

20
00:00:55,245 --> 00:00:57,260
the context of linear algebra, we like to

21
00:00:57,260 --> 00:00:59,660
think about transformations that take in some vector

22
00:00:59,660 --> 00:01:01,420
and spit out another vector.

23
00:01:02,460 --> 00:01:04,780
So why use the word transformation instead of

24
00:01:04,780 --> 00:01:06,620
function if they mean the same thing?

25
00:01:07,020 --> 00:01:08,860
Well, it's to be suggestive of a certain

26
00:01:08,860 --> 00:01:11,975
way to visualize this input output relation. You

27
00:01:11,975 --> 00:01:14,055
see, a great way to understand functions of

28
00:01:14,055 --> 00:01:16,135
vectors is to use movement.

29
00:01:16,855 --> 00:01:19,575
If a transformation takes some input vector to

30
00:01:19,575 --> 00:01:20,935
some output vector,

31
00:01:21,175 --> 00:01:23,975
we imagine that input vector moving over to

32
00:01:23,975 --> 00:01:24,855
the output vector.

33
00:01:25,650 --> 00:01:28,210
Then to understand the transformation as a whole,

34
00:01:28,370 --> 00:01:31,490
we might imagine watching every possible input vector

35
00:01:31,490 --> 00:01:34,370
move over to its corresponding output vector.

36
00:01:35,010 --> 00:01:36,850
It gets really crowded to think about all

37
00:01:36,850 --> 00:01:38,530
of the vectors all at once, each one

38
00:01:38,530 --> 00:01:40,575
as an arrow. So as I mentioned last

39
00:01:40,575 --> 00:01:43,055
video, a nice trick is to conceptualize each

40
00:01:43,055 --> 00:01:45,215
vector not as an arrow, but as a

41
00:01:45,215 --> 00:01:47,695
single point, the point where its tip sits.

42
00:01:47,935 --> 00:01:50,335
That way, to think about a transformation taking

43
00:01:50,335 --> 00:01:52,895
every possible input vector to some output vector,

44
00:01:53,160 --> 00:01:55,640
we watch every point in space moving to

45
00:01:55,640 --> 00:01:56,600
some other point.

46
00:01:57,240 --> 00:01:59,560
In the case of transformations in two dimensions,

47
00:01:59,560 --> 00:02:01,000
to get a better feel for the whole

48
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:02,840
shape of the transformation,

49
00:02:03,080 --> 00:02:04,280
I like to do this with all of

50
00:02:04,280 --> 00:02:05,800
the points on an infinite grid.

51
00:02:06,445 --> 00:02:08,205
I also sometimes like to keep a copy

52
00:02:08,205 --> 00:02:09,805
of the grid in the background just to

53
00:02:09,805 --> 00:02:11,565
help keep track of where everything ends up

54
00:02:11,565 --> 00:02:13,165
relative to where it starts.

55
00:02:14,845 --> 00:02:17,805
The effect for various transformations moving around all

56
00:02:17,805 --> 00:02:19,965
of the points in space is, you've gotta

57
00:02:19,965 --> 00:02:21,470
admit, beautiful.

58
00:02:21,870 --> 00:02:23,790
It gives the feeling of squishing and morphing

59
00:02:23,790 --> 00:02:24,830
space itself.

60
00:02:25,550 --> 00:02:28,590
As you can imagine though, arbitrary transformations

61
00:02:28,590 --> 00:02:30,190
can look pretty complicated.

62
00:02:30,510 --> 00:02:32,990
But luckily, linear algebra limits itself to a

63
00:02:32,990 --> 00:02:34,190
special type of transformation,

64
00:02:34,565 --> 00:02:37,445
ones that are easier to understand called linear

65
00:02:37,445 --> 00:02:38,565
transformations.

66
00:02:39,205 --> 00:02:42,085
Visually speaking, a transformation is linear if it

67
00:02:42,085 --> 00:02:43,365
has two properties.

68
00:02:43,685 --> 00:02:47,205
All lines must remain lines without getting curved,

69
00:02:47,525 --> 00:02:49,605
and the origin must remain fixed in place.

70
00:02:50,530 --> 00:02:52,850
For example, this right here would not be

71
00:02:52,850 --> 00:02:55,170
a linear transformation since the lines get all

72
00:02:55,170 --> 00:02:55,890
curvy.

73
00:02:56,130 --> 00:02:57,890
And this one right here, although it keeps

74
00:02:57,890 --> 00:02:58,850
the line straight,

75
00:02:59,010 --> 00:03:01,330
is not a linear transformation because it moves

76
00:03:01,330 --> 00:03:01,810
the origin.

77
00:03:02,615 --> 00:03:04,455
This one here fixes the origin, and it

78
00:03:04,455 --> 00:03:06,295
might look like it keeps lines straight, but

79
00:03:06,295 --> 00:03:08,135
that's just because I'm only showing the horizontal

80
00:03:08,135 --> 00:03:10,135
and vertical grid lines. When you see what

81
00:03:10,135 --> 00:03:11,975
it does to a diagonal line, it becomes

82
00:03:11,975 --> 00:03:13,815
clear that it's not at all linear since

83
00:03:13,815 --> 00:03:15,335
it turns that line all curvy.

84
00:03:16,760 --> 00:03:19,160
In general, you should think of linear transformations

85
00:03:19,160 --> 00:03:21,080
as keeping grid lines parallel

86
00:03:21,080 --> 00:03:22,600
and evenly spaced.

87
00:03:23,480 --> 00:03:25,960
Some linear transformations are simple to think about,

88
00:03:25,960 --> 00:03:27,880
like rotations about the origin.

89
00:03:28,120 --> 00:03:30,280
Others are a little trickier to describe with

90
00:03:30,280 --> 00:03:30,600
words.

91
00:03:32,045 --> 00:03:33,725
So how do you think you could describe

92
00:03:33,725 --> 00:03:34,845
these transformations

93
00:03:34,845 --> 00:03:35,725
numerically?

94
00:03:35,965 --> 00:03:38,445
If you were, say, programming some animations to

95
00:03:38,445 --> 00:03:40,685
make a video teaching the topic, what formula

96
00:03:40,685 --> 00:03:42,525
do you give the computer so that if

97
00:03:42,525 --> 00:03:43,965
you give it the coordinates of a vector,

98
00:03:44,240 --> 00:03:46,320
it can give you the coordinates of where

99
00:03:46,320 --> 00:03:47,520
that vector lands?

100
00:03:48,400 --> 00:03:50,400
It turns out that you only need to

101
00:03:50,400 --> 00:03:52,960
record where the two basis vectors I hat

102
00:03:52,960 --> 00:03:54,800
and j hat each land,

103
00:03:54,960 --> 00:03:56,560
and everything else will follow from that.

104
00:03:57,385 --> 00:04:00,185
For example, consider the vector v with coordinates

105
00:04:00,185 --> 00:04:03,305
negative one, two, meaning that it equals negative

106
00:04:03,305 --> 00:04:05,545
one times I hat plus two times j

107
00:04:05,545 --> 00:04:05,785
hat.

108
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:11,400
If we play some transformation and follow where

109
00:04:11,400 --> 00:04:13,160
all three of these vectors go,

110
00:04:13,400 --> 00:04:15,720
the property that grid lines remain parallel and

111
00:04:15,720 --> 00:04:18,600
evenly spaced has a really important consequence.

112
00:04:19,080 --> 00:04:20,920
The place where v lands will be negative

113
00:04:20,920 --> 00:04:23,400
one times the vector where I hat landed

114
00:04:22,995 --> 00:04:25,075
plus two times the vector where j hat

115
00:04:25,075 --> 00:04:25,715
landed.

116
00:04:26,035 --> 00:04:27,875
In other words, it started off as a

117
00:04:27,875 --> 00:04:29,875
certain linear combination of I hat and j

118
00:04:29,875 --> 00:04:31,955
hat, and it ends up as that same

119
00:04:31,955 --> 00:04:34,595
linear combination of where those two vectors landed.

120
00:04:35,490 --> 00:04:37,730
This means you can deduce where v must

121
00:04:37,730 --> 00:04:39,970
go based only on where I hat and

122
00:04:39,970 --> 00:04:41,250
j hat each land.

123
00:04:41,570 --> 00:04:43,170
This is why I like keeping a copy

124
00:04:43,170 --> 00:04:45,330
of the original grid in the background. For

125
00:04:45,330 --> 00:04:47,730
the transformation shown here, we can read off

126
00:04:47,730 --> 00:04:50,290
that I hat lands on the coordinates one,

127
00:04:50,290 --> 00:04:52,665
negative two, and j hat lands on the

128
00:04:52,665 --> 00:04:55,305
x axis over at the coordinates three, zero.

129
00:04:55,865 --> 00:04:58,025
This means that the vector represented by negative

130
00:04:58,025 --> 00:05:00,265
one I hat plus two times j hat

131
00:05:00,265 --> 00:05:02,585
ends up at negative one times the vector

132
00:05:02,585 --> 00:05:03,865
one, negative two,

133
00:05:04,105 --> 00:05:06,185
plus two times the vector three, zero.

134
00:05:07,080 --> 00:05:08,520
Adding that altogether,

135
00:05:08,680 --> 00:05:10,360
you can deduce that it has to land

136
00:05:10,360 --> 00:05:12,040
on the vector five, two.

137
00:05:14,440 --> 00:05:15,880
This is a good point to pause and

138
00:05:15,880 --> 00:05:17,640
ponder because it's pretty important.

139
00:05:18,440 --> 00:05:20,760
Now given that I'm actually showing you the

140
00:05:20,760 --> 00:05:21,560
full transformation,

141
00:05:21,885 --> 00:05:23,645
you could have just looked to see that

142
00:05:23,645 --> 00:05:25,645
v has the coordinates five two.

143
00:05:25,805 --> 00:05:27,645
But the cool part here is that this

144
00:05:27,645 --> 00:05:29,885
gives us a technique to deduce where any

145
00:05:29,885 --> 00:05:32,125
vectors land so long as we have a

146
00:05:32,125 --> 00:05:34,125
record of where I hat and j hat

147
00:05:34,125 --> 00:05:36,925
each land without needing to watch the transformation

148
00:05:36,925 --> 00:05:37,245
itself.

149
00:05:38,570 --> 00:05:41,130
Write the vector with more general coordinates x

150
00:05:41,130 --> 00:05:41,930
and y,

151
00:05:42,170 --> 00:05:43,770
and it will land on x times the

152
00:05:43,770 --> 00:05:46,330
vector where I hat lands, one negative two,

153
00:05:47,370 --> 00:05:49,370
plus y times the vector where j hat

154
00:05:49,370 --> 00:05:50,650
lands, three zero.

155
00:05:51,995 --> 00:05:54,155
Carrying out that sum, you see that it

156
00:05:54,155 --> 00:05:56,395
lands at one x plus three y,

157
00:05:56,555 --> 00:05:58,475
negative two x plus zero y.

158
00:05:58,875 --> 00:06:00,875
I give you any vector, and you can

159
00:06:00,875 --> 00:06:03,195
tell me where that vector lands using this

160
00:06:03,195 --> 00:06:03,595
formula.

161
00:06:04,960 --> 00:06:06,720
What all of this is saying is that

162
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:08,800
a two dimensional linear transformation

163
00:06:08,800 --> 00:06:12,080
is completely described by just four numbers,

164
00:06:12,240 --> 00:06:14,160
the two coordinates for where I hat lands

165
00:06:14,160 --> 00:06:16,160
and the two coordinates for where j hat

166
00:06:16,160 --> 00:06:16,800
lands.

167
00:06:16,960 --> 00:06:17,680
Isn't that cool?

168
00:06:18,285 --> 00:06:20,525
It's common to package these coordinates into a

169
00:06:20,525 --> 00:06:22,605
two by two grid of numbers called a

170
00:06:22,605 --> 00:06:23,965
two by two matrix,

171
00:06:24,205 --> 00:06:26,365
where you can interpret the columns as the

172
00:06:26,365 --> 00:06:28,845
two special vectors where I hat and j

173
00:06:28,845 --> 00:06:29,645
hat each land.

174
00:06:30,460 --> 00:06:32,220
If you're given a two by two matrix

175
00:06:32,220 --> 00:06:34,060
describing a linear transformation

176
00:06:34,060 --> 00:06:36,620
and some specific vector and you wanna know

177
00:06:36,620 --> 00:06:38,620
where that linear transformation

178
00:06:38,620 --> 00:06:39,980
takes that vector,

179
00:06:40,380 --> 00:06:41,980
you can take the coordinates of the vector,

180
00:06:42,645 --> 00:06:45,205
multiply them by the corresponding columns of the

181
00:06:45,205 --> 00:06:47,685
matrix, then add together what you get.

182
00:06:48,085 --> 00:06:50,325
This corresponds with the idea of adding the

183
00:06:50,325 --> 00:06:52,725
scaled versions of our new basis vectors.

184
00:06:54,820 --> 00:06:56,340
Let's see what this looks like in the

185
00:06:56,340 --> 00:06:59,060
most general case where your matrix has entries

186
00:06:59,060 --> 00:07:00,820
a, b, c, d.

187
00:07:01,060 --> 00:07:02,820
And remember, this matrix is just a way

188
00:07:02,820 --> 00:07:05,380
of packaging the information needed to describe a

189
00:07:05,380 --> 00:07:06,180
linear transformation.

190
00:07:06,595 --> 00:07:09,395
Always remember to interpret that first column a

191
00:07:09,395 --> 00:07:11,555
c as the place where the first basis

192
00:07:11,555 --> 00:07:14,115
vector lands and that second column b d

193
00:07:14,115 --> 00:07:16,115
as the place where the second basis vector

194
00:07:16,115 --> 00:07:16,755
lands.

195
00:07:17,475 --> 00:07:19,555
When we apply this transformation to some vector

196
00:07:19,555 --> 00:07:20,995
x y, what do you get?

197
00:07:22,050 --> 00:07:25,490
Well, it'll be x times a c plus

198
00:07:25,490 --> 00:07:27,330
y times b d.

199
00:07:28,130 --> 00:07:30,690
Putting this together, you get a vector a

200
00:07:30,690 --> 00:07:33,170
x plus b y, c x plus d

201
00:07:33,170 --> 00:07:33,410
y.

202
00:07:34,265 --> 00:07:36,825
You could even define this as matrix vector

203
00:07:36,825 --> 00:07:37,785
multiplication

204
00:07:37,785 --> 00:07:39,465
when you put the matrix on the left

205
00:07:39,465 --> 00:07:41,225
of the vector like it's a function.

206
00:07:41,625 --> 00:07:43,705
Then you could make high schoolers memorize this

207
00:07:43,705 --> 00:07:45,785
without showing them the crucial part that makes

208
00:07:45,785 --> 00:07:46,665
it feel intuitive.

209
00:07:48,250 --> 00:07:50,010
But isn't it more fun to think about

210
00:07:50,010 --> 00:07:52,650
these columns as the transformed versions of your

211
00:07:52,650 --> 00:07:54,890
basis vectors and to think about the results

212
00:07:54,890 --> 00:07:58,010
as the appropriate linear combination of those vectors?

213
00:08:00,825 --> 00:08:03,385
Let's practice describing a few linear transformations with

214
00:08:03,385 --> 00:08:04,185
matrices.

215
00:08:04,505 --> 00:08:07,065
For example, if we rotate all of space

216
00:08:07,065 --> 00:08:09,145
90 degrees counterclockwise,

217
00:08:09,305 --> 00:08:12,025
then I hat lands on the coordinates zero,

218
00:08:12,025 --> 00:08:12,265
one,

219
00:08:14,030 --> 00:08:16,430
and j hat lands on the coordinates negative

220
00:08:16,430 --> 00:08:17,550
one, zero.

221
00:08:17,950 --> 00:08:19,630
So the matrix we end up with has

222
00:08:19,630 --> 00:08:22,350
columns zero, one, negative one, zero.

223
00:08:23,150 --> 00:08:24,990
To figure out what happens to any vector

224
00:08:24,990 --> 00:08:27,310
after a 90 degree rotation, you could just

225
00:08:27,310 --> 00:08:29,925
multiply its coordinates by this matrix.

226
00:08:31,365 --> 00:08:33,445
Here's a fun transformation with a special name

227
00:08:33,445 --> 00:08:34,725
called a shear.

228
00:08:35,045 --> 00:08:37,365
In it, I hat remains fixed, so the

229
00:08:37,365 --> 00:08:39,525
first column of the matrix is one zero,

230
00:08:39,685 --> 00:08:42,325
but j hat moves over to the coordinates

231
00:08:42,325 --> 00:08:44,770
one one, which become the second column of

232
00:08:44,770 --> 00:08:45,570
the matrix.

233
00:08:45,970 --> 00:08:48,050
And at the risk of being redundant here,

234
00:08:48,050 --> 00:08:50,210
figuring out how a shear transforms a given

235
00:08:50,210 --> 00:08:53,410
vector comes down to multiplying this matrix by

236
00:08:53,410 --> 00:08:54,050
that vector.

237
00:08:55,665 --> 00:08:57,105
Let's say we wanna go the other way

238
00:08:57,105 --> 00:08:59,745
around, starting with a matrix, say with columns

239
00:08:59,745 --> 00:09:02,465
one two and three one, and we wanna

240
00:09:02,465 --> 00:09:05,425
deduce what its transformation looks like. Pause and

241
00:09:05,425 --> 00:09:06,625
take a moment to see if you can

242
00:09:06,625 --> 00:09:07,105
imagine it.

243
00:09:08,480 --> 00:09:10,320
One way to do this is to first

244
00:09:10,320 --> 00:09:12,560
move I hat to one two,

245
00:09:12,880 --> 00:09:15,280
then move j hat to three one,

246
00:09:15,520 --> 00:09:17,360
always moving the rest of space in such

247
00:09:17,360 --> 00:09:19,360
a way that keeps grid lines parallel and

248
00:09:19,360 --> 00:09:20,240
evenly spaced.

249
00:09:21,865 --> 00:09:23,545
If the vectors that I hat and j

250
00:09:23,545 --> 00:09:25,865
hat land on are linearly dependent,

251
00:09:26,105 --> 00:09:28,105
which if you recall from last video means

252
00:09:28,105 --> 00:09:30,025
that one is a scaled version of the

253
00:09:30,025 --> 00:09:32,425
other, it means that the linear transformation

254
00:09:32,760 --> 00:09:35,480
squishes all of two d space onto the

255
00:09:35,480 --> 00:09:38,120
line where those two vectors sit, also known

256
00:09:38,120 --> 00:09:40,680
as the one dimensional span of those two

257
00:09:40,680 --> 00:09:42,440
linearly dependent vectors.

258
00:09:44,855 --> 00:09:47,495
To sum up, linear transformations are a way

259
00:09:47,495 --> 00:09:49,895
to move around space such that grid lines

260
00:09:49,895 --> 00:09:52,615
remain parallel and evenly spaced and such that

261
00:09:52,615 --> 00:09:55,335
the origin remains fixed. Delightfully,

262
00:09:55,415 --> 00:09:57,735
these transformations can be described using only a

263
00:09:57,735 --> 00:10:00,360
handful of numbers, the coordinates of where each

264
00:10:00,360 --> 00:10:02,200
basis vector lands.

265
00:10:02,600 --> 00:10:05,160
Matrices give us a language to describe these

266
00:10:05,160 --> 00:10:06,120
transformations

267
00:10:06,200 --> 00:10:09,560
where the columns represent those coordinates, and matrix

268
00:10:09,560 --> 00:10:10,520
vector multiplication

269
00:10:10,785 --> 00:10:12,705
is just a way to compute what that

270
00:10:12,705 --> 00:10:15,025
transformation does to a given vector.

271
00:10:15,265 --> 00:10:17,665
The important takeaway here is that every time

272
00:10:17,665 --> 00:10:19,905
you see a matrix, you can interpret it

273
00:10:19,905 --> 00:10:22,145
as a certain transformation of space.

274
00:10:22,625 --> 00:10:24,920
Once you really digest this idea, you're in

275
00:10:24,920 --> 00:10:27,640
a great position to understand linear algebra deeply.

276
00:10:27,800 --> 00:10:29,960
